{
  "doc_id": "39616",
  "text": "MEG records activity in the brain based on the magnetic fields induced by synchronized neuronal currents [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] and can monitor the activation of synchronously firing neuronal populations with a submillisecond temporal resolution [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . However, since the magnetic signals of the brain vary between 10 2 (evoked cortical activity) and 10 3 femtoteslas (fT) (the human alpha rhythm), and the magnetic field of the earth is in the neighborhood of 10 9 fT, the method has to balance two problems: the weakness of the signal and the strength of the noise [CITATION_6] . These issues are addressed by using hundreds of extremely sensitive superconducting quantum interference devices incorporated in the whole head system (for recording simultaneously from the entire brain) and used in a magnetically shielded room [CITATION_7] .",
